item.description:
arXiv:2512.00328v1 Announce Type: new 
Abstract: The first observation of the decay $\Bp\rightarrow \proton \Lbar$ is presented, using proton-proton collision data collected by the LHCb experiment between 2016 and 2018 at a center-of-mass energy of $13\tev$, corresponding to an integrated luminosity of $5.4\invfb$. The signal significance exceeds seven standard deviations. Using the $\Bp \rightarrow \KS \pip$ decay as a normalization channel, the branching fraction is measured and combined with previous LHCb results based on data collected at 7 and $8\tev$ in 2011 and 2012, yielding \begin{eqnarray}
  \BF(\Bp\rightarrow \proton \Lbar) = (1.24\pm0.17\pm0.05\pm0.03)\times10^{-7}\,,\nonumber \end{eqnarray} where the first uncertainty is statistical, the second is systematic, and the third comes from the uncertainty on the branching fraction of the normalization channel. The $\Bp\rightarrow \proton \Lbar$ weak decay parameter is measured to be $\alpha_B = 0.87_{-0.29}^{+0.26} \pm 0.09$, indicating the presence of comparable S-wave and P-wave decay amplitudes.
